The path to nuclear disarmament
NEW YORK - Mass destruction weapons and disarmament represent one of the most difficult challenges that the world is currently facing. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote global well-being and find solutions to problems that do not respect borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of the highest importance.
My interest in this topic is based partly on personal experiences.
My home country of South Korea suffered from the devastation of conventional war and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
However, such threat scenarios obviously do not exist only in Asia.
Although the use of atomic weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that only applies to the use of such weapons really sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
However, the UN plays a decisive role in this process.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and educate to achieve our agreed-upon goals, and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and have grouped their commitments under the nuclear non-proliferation treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against a nuclear attack, which mainly explains the estimated 26,000 still existing weapons.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and new risks emerging that nuclear weapons will be used.
The world is still concerned about the nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns with peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we are facing a "nuclear renaissance" as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material, which must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are massive.
However, the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let's think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm Institute for International Peace Research), military spending rose last year to over $ 1.3 billion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study in which the total costs of nuclear weapons alone in the United States were estimated at over $ 5.8 billion, including future maintenance costs.
That's a huge investment by any definition, which could have been invested in many other productive goals.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers inherent in them have led to a global intellectual fire, as new life could be breathed into nuclear disarmament.
We have experienced the UN disarmament commission led by Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan established the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Citizen groups and nuclear-armed states have also submitted proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, which was introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
First: I call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to comply with their obligations under the treaty and to engage in negotiations on effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has been proposed for a long time in the UN.
I have sent a draft for such a convention to all UN members, which offers a good starting point.
The nuclear powers should deal with this issue together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiation forum for disarmament in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the US and Russia, with the goal of strongly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The proposal by Great Britain to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly inform the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear weapons deployment or the threat of it.
The Council could also call a summit on nuclear disarmament.
Nations that are not members of the nuclear disarmament treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: One-sided moratoriums for nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials are only to be allowed up to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to put the nuclear test ban treaty into effect, as well as incentives for the disarmament conference to immediately and without preconditions take up the talks on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Furthermore, I urgently call on all members of the nuclear disarmament treaty to urgently conclude their security agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily introduce the stricter security clauses of the additional protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no authoritative estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various additional measures are required.
To this belong the removal of other types of mass destruction weapons, new efforts against terrorism with mass destruction weapons, a limitation of the production and trade of conventional weapons and new weapon prohibitions, among others for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the atomic threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the most deadly weapons of the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks with mass destruction weapons.
These proposals offer a new beginning, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
